00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:02.000
Teacher:
 IT'S RIGHT FOR THE...

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:04.000
Brazelton:
 THESE TEENS DO HAVE
 SPECIAL ISSUES

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:08.000
WHICH EVERY HIGH SCHOOL
 SHOULD TRY TO UNDERSTAND
 AND SUPPORT.

00:11:08.000 --> 00:11:11.000
INDIVIDUAL AND GROUP
 COUNSELING

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:13.000
IS SCHEDULED
 FOR EVERY STUDENT.

00:11:13.000 --> 00:11:17.000
WE'RE TALKING
ABOUT WHAT HAPPENED WHEN
YOU TOLD YOUR MOTHER...

00:11:17.000 --> 00:11:19.000
Brazelton:
 THESE KIDS HAVE GONE
 THROUGH A LOT.

00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:21.000
...OR THE BABY'S FATHER

00:11:21.000 --> 00:11:25.000
- THAT YOU ARE PREGNANT.
  WHAT WAS THAT LIKE?
- Brazelton: JUST LISTEN.

00:11:25.000 --> 00:11:27.000
I WAS TERRIFIED
TO TELL MY MOTHER.

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:29.000
I DIDN'T TELL HER.

00:11:29.000 --> 00:11:32.000
I FOUND OUT WHEN I WAS THREE
MONTHS THAT I WAS PREGNANT,
AND I DIDN'T TELL HER.

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:34.000
I TOLD HER
INTO MY FIFTH MONTH.

00:11:34.000 --> 00:11:38.000
SHE WAS LIKE, "YOU
CAN'T STAY HERE ANYMORE.
I'M GOING TO DISOWN YOU."

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:40.000
BUT SHE GOT OVER THAT.
IT'S LIKE SHE'S HAPPY NOW.

00:11:41.000 --> 00:11:43.000
MAYBE SHE WAS MAD BECAUSE
I WAS STILL IN SCHOOL.

00:11:43.000 --> 00:11:45.000
THAT'S WHAT SHE WANTED ME
TO DO-- TO FINISH SCHOOL.

00:11:45.000 --> 00:11:48.000
I DIDN'T SHOW AT ALL.
I STARTED SHOWING
ONCE I TOLD HER.

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:51.000
I THOUGHT THAT
MY KID WAS HIDING,

00:11:51.000 --> 00:11:55.000
LIKE FEARING--
THE FEAR I FELT,
I FELT IT FELT THE FEAR.

00:11:55.000 --> 00:11:58.000
I HAD A FEAR OF TELLING
MY BOYFRIEND'S MOTHER,

00:11:58.000 --> 00:12:01.000
WHO WE KEPT IT FROM
FOR AWHILE.

00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:04.000
WE DIDN'T WANT TO TELL HER,
BUT SHE SAID SHE FIGURED IT
OUT BY HERSELF

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:07.000
BECAUSE MY EATING
HABITS CHANGED.

00:12:07.000 --> 00:12:10.000
SO EVERYBODY KNOWS NOW.

00:12:10.000 --> 00:12:13.000
HE TOOK IT COOL.
HE WAS LIKE, "I'M GOING
TO BE A GRANDFATHER.

00:12:13.000 --> 00:12:16.000
OH, MY GOD, AT 33,
I'M GOING TO BE
A GRANDFATHER!"

00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:19.000
- HOW ARE YOU ALL GOING TO
  TAKE CARE OF THIS CHILD?
- WE GOT TO GET A JOB.

00:12:20.000 --> 00:12:23.000
Brazelton:
 THE SCHOOL HAS TRAINED
 SENSITIVE TEACHERS,

00:12:23.000 --> 00:12:25.000
PEOPLE THE GIRLS
 CAN TRUST.

00:12:25.000 --> 00:12:27.000
- HE'S HAPPY.
- OKAY, IS HE MAKING
  ANY PREPARATIONS

00:12:27.000 --> 00:12:31.000
- TO SUPPORT THE CHILD
  AND YOU FINANCIALLY?
- YES.

00:12:31.000 --> 00:12:33.000
( overlapping dialogue )

00:12:33.000 --> 00:12:36.000
Brazelton:
 THE SCHOOL HAS BEEN
 A GREAT SUCCESS.

00:12:36.000 --> 00:12:38.000
Amaker:
 ORDINARILY, THE GIRLS
 ARE ALLOWED

00:12:38.000 --> 00:12:40.000
TO STAY FOR 18 MONTHS.

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:43.000
I CAN'T BEGIN TO COUNT
 THE NUMBER OF TIMES

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:44.000
AND THE NUMBER
 OF GIRLS

00:12:44.000 --> 00:12:48.000
WHO HAVE LITERALLY
 BEGGED US TO BE ALLOWED
 TO STAY HERE

00:12:48.000 --> 00:12:50.000
FOR MORE THAN
 THE 18 MONTHS.

00:12:50.000 --> 00:12:53.000
Brazelton:
 THESE GIRLS HAVE DREAMS

00:12:53.000 --> 00:12:56.000
LIKE ANY OTHER
 HIGH SCHOOL TEEN,

00:12:56.000 --> 00:12:59.000
SOMETHING EVERY SCHOOL
 SHOULD ENCOURAGE.

00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:01.000
Jiselle:
 AND I DO SEE MYSELF

00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:03.000
TRYING TO ACCOMPLISH
 SOMETHING.

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:05.000
I WANT TO WAKE UP
 EVERY DAY,

00:13:05.000 --> 00:13:08.000
AND WAKE UP TO SOMETHING
 I LOVE DOING.

00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:10.000
I WANT TO BE A DOCTOR.

00:13:10.000 --> 00:13:13.000
I KNOW I GOTTA GET GOOD GRADES
IN ORDER TO GET MYSELF
INTO A COLLEGE,

00:13:13.000 --> 00:13:16.000
TO START PREPARING MYSELF
 TO BECOME A DOCTOR.

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:19.000
Brazelton:
 A LOVE OF LEARNING,

00:13:19.000 --> 00:13:22.000
A LOVE OF CHILDREN,
 A LOVE OF LIFE.

00:13:22.000 --> 00:13:24.000
I WANT TO WAKE UP
TO SOMETHING I LOVE.

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:26.000
I WANT TO WAKE UP
TO THE PASSION I HAVE.

00:13:27.000 --> 00:13:29.000
Brazelton:
 NEXT, WE TALK TO PARENTS

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:31.000
ACROSS THE COUNTRY.

00:13:36.000 --> 00:13:39.000
Woman:
 WE'VE SOLD OUT.
 WE HAVE OVER 900 PEOPLE...

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:41.000
Brazelton:
 EACH YEAR WE TRAVEL
 ALL OVER AMERICA...

00:13:41.000 --> 00:13:43.000
Man:
 OUR COMMUNITY IS
 SO EXCITED ABOUT THIS.

00:13:43.000 --> 00:13:46.000
Brazelton:
 ...TO ANSWER QUESTIONS
 FROM THOUSANDS OF PARENTS.

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:49.000
Emcee:
 I'D LIKE TO WELCOME
 DR. T. BERRY BRAZELTON.

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:52.000
Brazelton:
 HERE ARE SOME OF THEM.

00:13:58.000 --> 00:14:00.000
HOW YOU DOIN'?
I HAD A QUESTION

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:02.000
ABOUT CONNECTING
AND BONDING.

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:06.000
YOU HAD TOUCHED UPON THE FACT
THAT FATHERS DEVELOP A BOND
WITH THE CHILDREN.

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:08.000
THEY'RE ALWAYS
PLAYING WITH THEM.

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:10.000
- WHEN THEY SEE THE FATHER,
  THEY GET EXCITED AND HAPPY.
- ISN'T THAT FUN?

00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:12.000
- YEAH, IT'S FUN.
- ( all laughing )

00:14:12.000 --> 00:14:15.000
- YOU LOOK LIKE
  YOU ENJOY IT, TOO.
- I HAVE A GOOD TIME.

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:18.000
I'LL BET THAT BOY
SURE ENJOYS IT.
IS IT A BOY?

00:14:18.000 --> 00:14:20.000
YEAH, TWO BOYS.
 I'M A FATHER OF TWO.

00:14:21.000 --> 00:14:22.000
SAY, FOR INSTANCE,
THERE WAS A SITUATION WHERE

00:14:22.000 --> 00:14:24.000
A MOTHER
HAD TO BE ABSENT

00:14:25.000 --> 00:14:27.000
AND THE FATHER WAS
REALLY THE ONLY ONE

00:14:27.000 --> 00:14:29.000
THAT HAD TO TAKE OVER
THE ROLE NOW,

00:14:29.000 --> 00:14:31.000
WOULD A CHILD BE ABLE
TO SWITCH FROM

00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:33.000
ALWAYS EXPECTING
TO PLAY AND BE HAPPY

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:36.000
AND EXPECTING THE FUN--

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:38.000
TO SEE YOU IN ANOTHER WAY?
ARE YOU A SINGLE PARENT?

00:14:38.000 --> 00:14:40.000
- YES.
- GOOD FOR YOU.

00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:43.000
I WAS WONDERING,
WOULD A BABY BE
ABLE TO ADJUST

00:14:43.000 --> 00:14:45.000
- TO THE NEW BOND
  WITH THE FATHER?
- YEAH.

00:14:45.000 --> 00:14:48.000
WHAT KIND OF EFFECTS
WOULD IT HAVE ON THE CHILD

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:50.000
TO LOSE THE BOND
WITH THE MOTHER?

00:14:50.000 --> 00:14:54.000
WELL, IT HAS SOME
PRETTY POWERFUL EFFECTS,
TO LOSE YOUR MOTHER.

00:14:54.000 --> 00:14:58.000
AND YOU ALWAYS WONDER,
"IF I'VE LOST ONE PARENT,
WILL I LOSE THE OTHER?"

00:14:58.000 --> 00:15:00.000
SO YOU SHOULD BE
 PREPARED ALL THE TIME

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:02.000
FOR THEM TO BRING UP
QUESTIONS--

00:15:02.000 --> 00:15:04.000
"ARE YOU GOING OFF
TO LEAVE ME?"

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:07.000
AND IF YOU GO OFF TO WORK,
"ARE YOU COMING BACK?"

00:15:07.000 --> 00:15:10.000
AND RATHER THAN
GETTING EXASPERATED
WITH THAT QUESTION,

00:15:10.000 --> 00:15:13.000
REALIZE THAT THEY NEED IT
TO REASSURE THEMSELVES

00:15:13.000 --> 00:15:17.000
THAT YOU CARE
DEEPLY ABOUT THEM.

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:20.000
AND WHEN YOU GET A CHANCE,
I'D EVEN SAY THAT
ABOUT THEIR MOMMY--

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:22.000
"SHE'S GONE OFF,
AND WE DON'T KNOW
WHERE SHE IS,

00:15:22.000 --> 00:15:25.000
BUT I'LL BET SHE MISSES
YOU LIKE EVERYTHING."

00:15:25.000 --> 00:15:28.000
SO, YOU KNOW, GIVE THEM
BACK THAT FEELING

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:30.000
THEY'RE SURROUNDED
BY PEOPLE

00:15:30.000 --> 00:15:32.000
WHO CARE ABOUT THEM,
AND THEY ARE.

00:15:32.000 --> 00:15:34.000
LOOK AT THE WAY
 YOU TALK ABOUT 'EM.

00:15:34.000 --> 00:15:37.000
AND I LOVE THE SENSITIVITY
OF YOUR QUESTION.

00:15:37.000 --> 00:15:39.000
SURE, THEY WILL.

00:15:39.000 --> 00:15:42.000
THEY'LL FIND NOT ONLY
THEY PLAY WITH YOU,

00:15:42.000 --> 00:15:44.000
WHICH YOU ENJOY
AND THEY ENJOY,

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:47.000
BUT THEY'LL ALSO FIND
THE OTHER SIDE OF YOU,

00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:50.000
THE NURTURING SIDE,
AND THEY'LL PLAY ON IT.

00:15:50.000 --> 00:15:52.000
AND THEY'LL WANT YOU
TO CUDDLE 'EM,

00:15:52.000 --> 00:15:55.000
AND WANT YOU TO SING
TO 'EM AT NIGHT,
OR READ TO 'EM AT NIGHT.

00:15:56.000 --> 00:15:57.000
AND I WOULD
GIVE IN TO THAT

00:15:58.000 --> 00:15:59.000
AND BE AS NURTURING
AS YOU CAN.

00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:02.000
I DON'T KNOW WHETHER
 IT MAKES YOU FEEL
 UNCOMFORTABLE OR NOT

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:05.000
WHEN YOU HAVE TO
 BE LIKE THAT.  GOOD.

00:16:05.000 --> 00:16:09.000
ANOTHER THING WAS THAT
YOU HAD TALKED ABOUT ROLES
OF A FATHER AND A MOTHER,

00:16:09.000 --> 00:16:12.000
AND THE WAY THE FATHER
HAS TO COME UP AND SHOW
THE CHILD THE WORLD.

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:15.000
CAN A FATHER SWITCH
ROLES AND RAISE

00:16:15.000 --> 00:16:17.000
A HEALTHY, MENTALLY
AND PHYSICALLY, CHILD?

00:16:17.000 --> 00:16:19.000
- YEAH.
- HE CAN?

00:16:19.000 --> 00:16:22.000
IT'S FASCINATING
TO ME THAT A CHILD
IN A SINGLE-PARENT FAMILY

00:16:22.000 --> 00:16:26.000
WILL LOOK FOR
TWO SEPARATE ROLES
IN THE PARENT,

00:16:26.000 --> 00:16:29.000
AND IF THEY DON'T FIND
ENOUGH OF THAT ROLE,

00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:32.000
THEY'LL LOOK OUTSIDE
AND SHOW SOME HUNGER.

00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:36.000
AS LONG AS YOU DON'T FEEL
UNCOMFORTABLE ABOUT
DOING IT WITH THEM,

00:16:36.000 --> 00:16:39.000
THEY'RE LUCKY,
LUCKY KIDS.

00:16:39.000 --> 00:16:41.000
SO KEEP IT UP.
 I'LL BET HE LOOKS TO YOU

00:16:41.000 --> 00:16:44.000
FOR WAYS TO MASTER THINGS
ANYWAY, DOESN'T HE?

00:16:44.000 --> 00:16:47.000
- YEAH.
- THAT'S WONDERFUL.

00:16:47.000 --> 00:16:49.000
- DOESN'T THAT MAKE
  YOU FEEL GOOD?
- IT MAKES ME FEEL GOOD.

00:16:49.000 --> 00:16:53.000
I DON'T LIKE TO KEEP
TOUCHING ON THE SIDE
THAT I'M VERY SENSITIVE

00:16:53.000 --> 00:16:55.000
BECAUSE IT KIND OF
FEELS WEIRD WHEN YOU SAY,

00:16:55.000 --> 00:16:58.000
- "THIS MAN IS
  VERY SENSITIVE."
- ( audience laughs )

00:16:58.000 --> 00:17:02.000
Brazelton: DO YOU FEEL LIKE
 YOU'RE TAKING A MOTHER'S
 ROLE AWAY FROM HER?

00:17:02.000 --> 00:17:04.000
- YEAH, SOMETIMES.
- DO YOU?

00:17:04.000 --> 00:17:06.000
YOU KNOW, TO ME
THAT'S THE PASSION

00:17:06.000 --> 00:17:10.000
OF WANTING TO GIVE
THIS LITTLE BOY
EVERYTHING YOU CAN.

00:17:10.000 --> 00:17:12.000
THAT IS SO GREAT.

00:17:12.000 --> 00:17:14.000
AND HE'S LEARNING
NURTURING FROM YOU

00:17:15.000 --> 00:17:18.000
AS WELL AS LEARNING
HOW TO BE A MAN.
IT COULDN'T BE BETTER.

00:17:18.000 --> 00:17:22.000
I GUESS THE NURTURING PART
 COMES FROM THE ABSENCE
 OF MY FATHER.

00:17:22.000 --> 00:17:25.000
SO KNOWING WHAT I NEEDED
IS WHAT I GIVE TO HIM NOW.

00:17:25.000 --> 00:17:28.000
SO YOU'RE REALLY
DOING EVERYTHING YOU CAN
FOR THIS KID, AREN'T YOU?

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:30.000
I'M TRYING TO.

00:17:30.000 --> 00:17:32.000
GREAT.
 I REALLY ADMIRE YOU.

00:17:32.000 --> 00:17:34.000
THANK YOU VERY MUCH.

00:17:40.000 --> 00:17:42.000
HI.  MY NAME'S DANIELE.

00:17:42.000 --> 00:17:44.000
I'M CONCERNED IF THERE'S
 ANY LONG-TERM EFFECTS

00:17:44.000 --> 00:17:47.000
IF WE MOVE AROUND A LOT,

00:17:47.000 --> 00:17:50.000
MOVED A LOT, LIKE,
FROM PLACE TO PLACE

00:17:50.000 --> 00:17:52.000
SINCE THE CHILD
WAS BORN.

00:17:52.000 --> 00:17:54.000
SHE'S EIGHT MONTHS OLD NOW.

00:17:54.000 --> 00:17:57.000
ARE YOU A SINGLE MOTHER?

00:17:57.000 --> 00:17:59.000
- NO.
- NO?

00:17:59.000 --> 00:18:01.000
WELL, WHY ARE YOU
 MOVING AROUND?

00:18:01.000 --> 00:18:03.000
WELL, I LIVE
WITH A BOYFRIEND,

00:18:03.000 --> 00:18:07.000
BUT WE'RE NOT MARRIED.
WE LIVE WITH HIS FAMILY.

00:18:07.000 --> 00:18:09.000
IS IT A STABLE SITUATION
BETWEEN YOU?

00:18:09.000 --> 00:18:11.000
- NOT SO SURE?
- NOT REALLY.

00:18:12.000 --> 00:18:14.000
SO YOU'RE WORRIED ABOUT
THAT, TOO, AREN'T YOU?

00:18:14.000 --> 00:18:18.000
YEAH.  I'M JUST CONCERNED
IF THERE'S ANYTHING THAT--

00:18:18.000 --> 00:18:20.000
IS SHE GOING
TO BE INSECURE?

00:18:20.000 --> 00:18:24.000
IS THERE ANYTHING THAT CAN
AFFECT HER DOWN THE ROAD

00:18:24.000 --> 00:18:26.000
IF SHE DOESN'T HAVE...

00:18:26.000 --> 00:18:28.000
THAT STABLE
LIVING ENVIRONMENT

00:18:28.000 --> 00:18:30.000
IF WE CONTINUE TO MOVE
FROM PLACE TO PLACE?

00:18:30.000 --> 00:18:32.000
WELL, SURE.

00:18:32.000 --> 00:18:35.000
THAT'S A STRESS ON HER
AND, OF COURSE,
IT IS ON YOU, TOO,

00:18:35.000 --> 00:18:37.000
'CAUSE IT'S MORE
OF A STRESS ON YOU.

00:18:37.000 --> 00:18:40.000
I CAN FEEL YOUR EMOTION
AS YOU TALK ABOUT IT.

00:18:41.000 --> 00:18:42.000
SO I DON'T THINK
 YOU'RE HAVING

00:18:43.000 --> 00:18:46.000
A VERY EASY TIME WITH IT
 EITHER, ARE YOU?

00:18:46.000 --> 00:18:48.000
- IT'S DIFFICULT.
- MM-HMM.

00:18:48.000 --> 00:18:51.000
I'M BASICALLY MORE CONCERNED
ABOUT THE MOVING AROUND

00:18:51.000 --> 00:18:54.000
AND NOT HAVING
ANYTHING STABLE,

00:18:54.000 --> 00:18:56.000
IF THAT'S GONNA
AFFECT HER.

00:18:56.000 --> 00:18:58.000
I DON'T THINK IT'S THE HOME
THAT'S THE STABILITY.

00:18:58.000 --> 00:19:01.000
I THINK IT'S
THE RELATIONSHIPS THAT IS.

00:19:01.000 --> 00:19:04.000
SO THE MORE SECURE
YOUR RELATIONSHIP
WITH HER IS,

00:19:04.000 --> 00:19:06.000
AND HIS RELATIONSHIP
WITH HER,

00:19:06.000 --> 00:19:09.000
AND EVEN HIS FAMILY'S
RELATIONSHIP--

00:19:09.000 --> 00:19:11.000
- YOUR FAMILY
  IS NOT NEARBY?
- NO.

00:19:11.000 --> 00:19:14.000
AND YOU MISS 'EM?

00:19:14.000 --> 00:19:17.000
THEY DON'T LIVE
THAT FAR AWAY, BUT WE'RE
JUST NOT THAT CLOSE.

00:19:17.000 --> 00:19:20.000
Brazelton: 
 AND YOU WISH
 THAT YOU WERE.

00:19:20.000 --> 00:19:22.000
THIS IS WHAT A BABY
CALLS UP IN YOU, ISN'T IT?

00:19:22.000 --> 00:19:25.000
THAT YOU WISH YOU COULD GET
BACK TO YOUR OWN PARENTS

00:19:25.000 --> 00:19:28.000
AND GET THEM
 TO NURTURE YOU.

00:19:29.000 --> 00:19:31.000
IT'S REALLY HARD
 WHEN YOU CAN'T,

00:19:31.000 --> 00:19:34.000
AND THIS IS WHAT YOU'RE
 MISSING, ISN'T IT?

00:19:34.000 --> 00:19:36.000
MM-HMM.
BUT YOU KNOW

00:19:36.000 --> 00:19:39.000
WHO'S THE MOST IMPORTANT
TO THAT BABY?

00:19:39.000 --> 00:19:41.000
YOU.

00:19:41.000 --> 00:19:43.000
AND THE WAY
YOUR FACE LIGHTS UP,

00:19:43.000 --> 00:19:46.000
AND THE WAY YOU, YOU KNOW,
 ARE SO CONCERNED ABOUT HER,

00:19:47.000 --> 00:19:50.000
I KNOW SHE'S GOT
 MONEY IN THE BANK.

00:19:50.000 --> 00:19:52.000
SHE'S A LUCKY
 LITTLE GIRL.

00:19:52.000 --> 00:19:56.000
- THANKS.
- YOU DON'T LOOK
  LIKE YOU BELIEVE IT.

00:19:56.000 --> 00:19:58.000
I DO.

00:19:58.000 --> 00:20:00.000
SO THERE ISN'T, LIKE,

00:20:00.000 --> 00:20:04.000
MUCH SERIOUS LONG-TERM
EFFECTS WITH--

00:20:04.000 --> 00:20:07.000
AS LONG AS HER FAMILY--
AS LONG AS WE'RE
CLOSE TO HER

00:20:07.000 --> 00:20:09.000
AND SHE'S
WELL TAKEN CARE OF,

00:20:09.000 --> 00:20:11.000
EVERYTHING'S
PRETTY MUCH OKAY?

00:20:11.000 --> 00:20:14.000
WELL, THE FIRST FEW YEARS
ARE THE MOST CRITICAL.

00:20:14.000 --> 00:20:18.000
AND THE MORE YOU CAN
SURROUND HER WITH PEOPLE
WHO CARE ABOUT HER--

00:20:18.000 --> 00:20:21.000
AND LET THEM
LET HER KNOW IT--
THE SURER SHE'LL BE,

00:20:21.000 --> 00:20:23.000
AND WHATEVER
SORT OF BUFFETING

00:20:23.000 --> 00:20:25.000
SHE HAS TO GO
THROUGH LATER,

00:20:25.000 --> 00:20:27.000
SHE'LL BE
READIER FOR IT.

00:20:27.000 --> 00:20:30.000
OKAY.  THANK YOU.

00:20:36.000 --> 00:20:38.000
Brazelton:
 FOR TAPES AND
 TRANSCRIPTS, CALL:

00:20:42.000 --> 00:20:44.000
OR LOG ON AT:

00:20:48.000 --> 00:20:50.000
ON PARENTING,"

00:20:50.000 --> 00:20:53.000
PRESENTED BY THE PARENTING
 INSTITUTE AT PAMPERS.COM.

00:20:53.000 --> 00:20:55.000
YOU KNOW,
THE OLD SAYING IS

00:20:55.000 --> 00:20:57.000
"CHILDREN RAISING CHILDREN,"

00:20:57.000 --> 00:21:00.000
AND IN SOME RESPECTS
THAT'S TRUE.

00:21:00.000 --> 00:21:02.000
BUT I HOPE YOU'VE SEEN THAT,
GIVEN A CHANCE,

00:21:02.000 --> 00:21:06.000
THESE YOUNG PEOPLE
CAN TURN OUT TO BE
WONDERFUL PARENTS,

00:21:06.000 --> 00:21:08.000
AND THEIR CHILDREN,
WONDERFUL KIDS.

00:21:09.000 --> 00:21:12.000
IT'S UP TO US NOT TO LABEL
THEM WITH OUR BIASES

00:21:12.000 --> 00:21:15.000
BUT TO UNDERSTAND THEM
AND HELP THEM

00:21:15.000 --> 00:21:17.000
BY OFFERING THEM
AND THEIR CHILDREN

00:21:17.000 --> 00:21:21.000
THE SUPPORT THEY NEED
TO SUCCEED.

00:21:27.000 --> 00:21:31.000
( theme music playing )